    <item>
      <title>Four Ways Or One Way</title>
      <link>/wiaposts/four-ways-or-one-way/</link>
      <pubDate>Wed, 27 Feb 2019 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <author>hari@dasarpai.com (Dr. Hari Thapliyaal)</author>
      <guid>/wiaposts/four-ways-or-one-way/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;
    &lt;figure&gt;
      &lt;img class=&#34;my-0 rounded-md&#34; loading=&#34;lazy&#34; src=&#34;/assets/images/wiapost/5092-Four-Ways-Or-One-Way.jpg&#34; alt=&#34;Four Ways Or One Way&#34; /&gt;
      
    &lt;/figure&gt;
&lt;/p&gt;


&lt;h1 class=&#34;relative group&#34;&gt;Four Ways Or One Way 
    &lt;div id=&#34;four-ways-or-one-way&#34; class=&#34;anchor&#34;&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
    
    &lt;span
        class=&#34;absolute top-0 w-6 transition-opacity opacity-0 ltr:-left-6 rtl:-right-6 not-prose group-hover:opacity-100&#34;&gt;
        &lt;a class=&#34;group-hover:text-primary-300 dark:group-hover:text-neutral-700&#34;
            style=&#34;text-decoration-line: none !important;&#34; href=&#34;#four-ways-or-one-way&#34; aria-label=&#34;Anchor&#34;&gt;#&lt;/a&gt;
    &lt;/span&gt;        
    
&lt;/h1&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Generally, people think,  &lt;br&gt;
Bhakti Yoga, Karma Yoga,  &lt;br&gt;
Raj Yoga, Gyana Yoga  &lt;br&gt;
are the four parallel paths in life,  &lt;br&gt;
which leads to the same goal.  &lt;br&gt;
Hence, they think to walk on any road,  &lt;br&gt;
and we will reach the same place.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;If you like road analogy  &lt;br&gt;
then know it as only one road,  &lt;br&gt;
which you travel with four kinds of wealth.  &lt;br&gt;
Every moment, every day, and phase of life  &lt;br&gt;
based on the need you use  &lt;br&gt;
different wealth and keep moving.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
      
    </item>
    
    <item>
      <title>Moksha The God In Vedanta</title>
      <link>/wiaposts/moksha-the-god-in-vedanta/</link>
      <pubDate>Mon, 04 Feb 2019 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <author>hari@dasarpai.com (Dr. Hari Thapliyaal)</author>
      <guid>/wiaposts/moksha-the-god-in-vedanta/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;
    &lt;figure&gt;
      &lt;img class=&#34;my-0 rounded-md&#34; loading=&#34;lazy&#34; src=&#34;/assets/images/wiapost/5091-Moksha-The-God-In-Vedanta.jpg&#34; alt=&#34;Moksha The God In Vedanta&#34; /&gt;
      
    &lt;/figure&gt;
&lt;/p&gt;


&lt;h1 class=&#34;relative group&#34;&gt;Moksha The God In Vedanta 
    &lt;div id=&#34;moksha-the-god-in-vedanta&#34; class=&#34;anchor&#34;&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
    
    &lt;span
        class=&#34;absolute top-0 w-6 transition-opacity opacity-0 ltr:-left-6 rtl:-right-6 not-prose group-hover:opacity-100&#34;&gt;
        &lt;a class=&#34;group-hover:text-primary-300 dark:group-hover:text-neutral-700&#34;
            style=&#34;text-decoration-line: none !important;&#34; href=&#34;#moksha-the-god-in-vedanta&#34; aria-label=&#34;Anchor&#34;&gt;#&lt;/a&gt;
    &lt;/span&gt;        
    
&lt;/h1&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The God of Upanishad is not that  &lt;br&gt;
what we “speak about” but the speaker!&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Not that which eye can see  &lt;br&gt;
but through which eyes see.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Not that which you pray  &lt;br&gt;
but that in the absence of which  &lt;br&gt;
you cannot pray.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The word “Maya” of Vedanta doesn’t  &lt;br&gt;
mean illusion nor it means it is false.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
      
    </item>
    
